import demeter.euler as euler
import demeter.directions as dirs
import itertools

import scipy.ndimage as ndimage
import scipy.special as special

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import tifffile as tf
from skimage.filters import threshold_otsu
leaf = './example_data/copo.tiff'

img = tf.imread(leaf)
# Convert image to grayscale if it has multiple channels
if img.ndim == 3 and img.shape[2] > 1:
    img = np.mean(img, axis=2).astype(img.dtype)
# Convert grayscale image to binary using Otsu's threshold

thresh = threshold_otsu(img)
img = (img > thresh).astype(np.uint8)

Cells = euler.CubicalComplex(img).complexify()

directions = dirs.regular_directions(50, dims=2)
bbox_=(-100,100)
ect = Cells.ECT2(directions, T=32, bbox=bbox_)

plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray');

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Supongamos que ect es de forma (T, num_directions)
# Por ejemplo: ect = ECT(directions, T=32)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.imshow(ect, aspect='auto', cmap='viridis', origin='lower')

plt.colorbar(label='Euler Characteristic')
plt.title('ECT de un Copo de Nieve', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel(r'$\omega$', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel(r'$a$', fontsize=14)

# Opcional: etiquetas en eje x con ángulos (si están uniformemente espaciados en [0, 2π])
num_dirs = ect.shape[1]
x_ticks = np.linspace(0, num_dirs - 1, 9)
x_labels = [r'$0$', r'$\frac{\pi}{4}$', r'$\frac{\pi}{2}$', r'$\frac{3\pi}{4}$',
            r'$\pi$', r'$\frac{5\pi}{4}$', r'$\frac{3\pi}{2}$', r'$\frac{7\pi}{4}$', r'$2\pi$']
plt.xticks(ticks=x_ticks, labels=x_labels)

# Opcional: etiquetas del eje y si conoces el rango de alturas
# Las alturas están en bbox_, que es una tupla (min_a, max_a)
min_a, max_a = bbox_
y_ticks = np.linspace(0, ect.shape[0] - 1, 5)
y_labels = np.round(np.linspace(min_a, max_a, 5), 2)
plt.yticks(ticks=y_ticks, labels=y_labels)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# Supón que ect tiene shape (T, N)
T, N = ect.shape

# Eje angular (omega) y eje a (altura del filtrado)
theta = np.linspace(0, 2 * np.pi, N)
a = np.linspace(-100, 100, T)  # puedes ajustar el rango real si lo sabes

# Crear una malla (grid) cilíndrica
Theta, A = np.meshgrid(theta, a)
R = 1  # radio del cilindro

# Coordenadas cilíndricas a cartesianas
X = R * np.cos(Theta)
Y = R * np.sin(Theta)
Z = A

# Crear la figura 3D
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(4, 4))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

# Dibujar el cilindro con la matriz como colores
surf = ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, facecolors=plt.cm.viridis((ect - np.min(ect)) / (np.ptp(ect))),
                       rstride=1, cstride=1, linewidth=0.5, edgecolor='w', antialiased=True)

# Opcional: agregar colorbar
mappable = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap='viridis')
mappable.set_array(ect)
# fig.colorbar(mappable, shrink=0.5, aspect=10, label='Euler Characteristic')

# Ajustes visuales
# ax.set_title('ECT sobre el cilindro')
ax.set_axis_off()  # para un efecto más limpio

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.axes_grid1 import make_axes_locatable

# Supongamos que ya tienes los vértices:
verts = Cells.cells[0]  # matriz Nx2

# Define ángulos y direcciones
angles = [np.pi/4, 3*np.pi/2]#, 5*np.pi/4, 7*np.pi/4]
directions = [np.array([np.cos(a), np.sin(a)]) for a in angles]

# Límites para color (puedes usar el bbox si prefieres)
vmin, vmax = -100, 100

# Crear figura
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 10))
axs = axs.flatten()

for i, omega in enumerate(directions):
    heights = np.dot(verts, omega)

    # Crear eje y divisor
    ax = axs[i]
    im = ax.scatter(verts[:, 0], verts[:, 1], c=heights,
                    cmap='viridis', vmin=vmin, vmax=vmax, s=5)

    ax.set_title(r'$f_\omega$ con $\omega = {:.2f}\pi$'.format(angles[i]/np.pi))
    ax.axis('equal')
    ax.axis('off')

    # Añadir barra de color individual
    divider = make_axes_locatable(ax)
    cax = divider.append_axes("right", size="5%", pad=0.05)
    plt.colorbar(im, cax=cax)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Dirección fija
angle = 2*np.pi/3
omega = np.array([np.cos(angle), np.sin(angle)])

# Calcular alturas
heights = np.sum(verts * omega, axis=1)

# Valores de a (umbrales)
levels = [-50, -30, 0, 30, 60]

# Calcular ECC
T = 100
bbox = (-100, 100)
ecc = Cells.ECC(heights, T=T, bbox=bbox)
a_vals = np.linspace(bbox[0], bbox[1], T)

# Crear figura
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 3, figsize=(14, 8))
axs = axs.flatten()

for i, a in enumerate(levels):
    mask = heights <= a
    axs[i].scatter(verts[mask, 0], verts[mask, 1], c=heights[mask],
                   cmap='viridis', vmin=bbox[0], vmax=bbox[1], s=5)
    axs[i].set_title(r'$K_{{{}}}$'.format(a))
    axs[i].axis('equal')
    axs[i].axis('off')

# ECC en último panel
axs[-1].plot(a_vals, ecc, lw=2)
axs[-1].set_title(r'ECC for $\omega = 2\pi/3$')
axs[-1].set_xlabel(r'$a$')
axs[-1].set_ylabel(r'$\chi(K_a)$')
axs[-1].grid(True)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

T = 32  # Número de niveles para la filtración
angles = [np.pi/4, 3*np.pi/2]#, 5*np.pi/4, 7*np.pi/4]
directions = [np.array([np.cos(a), np.sin(a)]) for a in angles]

verts = Cells.cells[0]  # Vértices del complejo
bbox = (-100, 100)  # Asegúrate de que sea coherente con la visualización anterior

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

for direction, angle in zip(directions, angles):
    heights = np.sum(verts * direction, axis=1)  # en vez de np.dot
    ecc = Cells.ECC(heights, T=T, bbox=bbox)
    plt.plot(ecc, lw=2, label=r'$\omega = {:.2f}\pi$'.format(angle / np.pi))

plt.title('Euler Characteristic Curves (ECC) for selected directions', fontsize=15)
plt.xlabel('Threshold bin', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Euler Characteristic', fontsize=12)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
